1. Can you explain the differences among these three concepts (CI/CD)?

EXPLAIN IN THIS ANSWER:-
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ğŸ‘‰ "CI/CD stands for Continuous Integration, Continuous Delivery, and Continuous Deployment,
    three essential DevOps practices that automate software development and deployment."

ğŸ”¹ 1. Continuous Integration (CI):
ğŸ‘‰ Focus: Automating code integration & testing.
ğŸ‘‰ Process: Developers frequently merge code into a shared repository, triggering automated builds and tests.
ğŸ‘‰ Goal: Detect and fix issues early, ensuring code quality.

ğŸ”¹ 2. Continuous Delivery (CD):
ğŸ‘‰ Focus: Automating deployments up to a staging/pre-production environment.
ğŸ‘‰ Process: Code is built, tested, and ready for manual approval before deploying to production.
ğŸ‘‰ Goal: Ensure every code change is production-ready.

ğŸ”¹ 3. Continuous Deployment (CD):
ğŸ‘‰ Focus: Fully automating deployments to production without manual approval.
ğŸ‘‰ Process: If all tests pass, code is automatically deployed to production.
ğŸ‘‰ Goal: Enable rapid, risk-free releases.

ğŸ”¹ Real-World Use Case:
ğŸ‘‰ "In my DMS project, we used CI/CD pipelines to automate builds, testing, and deployments, 
    CI ensured bug-free code, Continuous Delivery enabled manual approval before production, and 
    Continuous Deployment allowed seamless, automated releases."
