â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ğŸ‘‰ "Jenkins supports multiple ways to trigger builds, ensuring automation and flexibility in CI/CD pipelines. 
     The most common methods include manual triggers, webhooks, scheduled builds, polling SCM, and triggering from other jobs."

âœ… 1. Manual Trigger (Run Job Manually)
ğŸ“Œ How?
ğŸ‘‰ Go to Jenkins Dashboard â†’ Select Job â†’ Click â€˜Build Nowâ€™
âœ”  Used for on-demand builds during debugging or testing.

âœ… 2. Webhooks (GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket Triggers)
ğŸ“Œ How?
ğŸ‘‰ Configure a webhook in GitHub/GitLab/Bitbucket to notify Jenkins on code push or pull request.
ğŸ‘‰ In Jenkins, set "Build when a change is pushed to GitHub" under job configuration.
âœ”  Automatically triggers builds when new code is pushed.

âœ… 3. SCM Polling (Checking for Code Changes in Git Repo)
ğŸ“Œ How?
ğŸ‘‰ Enable "Poll SCM" in job settings and define a schedule (e.g., every 5 minutes):

âœ… 4. Scheduled Builds (Cron Jobs in Jenkins)
ğŸ“Œ How?
ğŸ‘‰ Use Jenkins' "Build periodically" option and set a cron schedule.
ğŸ‘‰ Example (Run every night at 2 AM)
