16. How would you scale Jenkins to handle an increasing number of builds?
    Can u explain the master-slave architecture in jenkins?

EXPLAIN IN THIS ANSWER:-
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
âœ… 1. Components of Master-Slave Architecture:
âœ”  Jenkins Master (Controller):
ğŸ‘‰ Jenkins UI, job scheduling, and managing build execution.
ğŸ‘‰ Assigns jobs to slaves (agents) based on labels and configurations.
ğŸ‘‰ Stores job configurations, plugins, and logs.

âœ”  Jenkins Slaves (Agents):
ğŸ‘‰ Executes build jobs assigned by the master.
ğŸ‘‰ Can run on different operating systems (Linux, Windows, Mac).
ğŸ‘‰ May have specific tools or dependencies installed for specialized builds.

âœ… 2. How Jenkins Master-Slave Works:
1ï¸âƒ£ Master schedules a build job based on triggers (SCM changes, manual, or scheduled).
2ï¸âƒ£ Master assigns the job to an appropriate slave based on labels, resources, and availability.
3ï¸âƒ£ Slave executes the build using the specified environment (Docker, Maven, Node.js, etc.).
4ï¸âƒ£ Results are sent back to the master for logging and reporting.

âœ” Parallel execution is possible if multiple slaves are available.

âœ… 3. How to Set Up Jenkins Agents:
1ï¸âƒ£ Install and configure the "Jenkins SSH Build Agents" plugin.
2ï¸âƒ£ Connect remote machines as agents using SSH.
3ï¸âƒ£ In job configuration, specify the agent label to execute builds on specific nodes.
